                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14540941" author="dimaspivak" created="Tue, 12 May 2015 22:52:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We actually did this for a time at Cloudera in hopes of better utilizing hosts, but found that tests would become flakey, even if run in separate containers, because of resource contention; it really seems that HBase tests need to be the only executor on a pretty beefy Jenkins slave. I&apos;d be happy to post up the Dockerfile I used to build the hbase-test-slave image that we used, though.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14554801" author="busbey" created="Thu, 21 May 2015 18:22:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;presuming &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-13525&quot; title=&quot;Update test-patch to leverage Apache Yetus&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-13525&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-13525&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; goes through we&apos;ll get this for free for precommit.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The main driver for Hadoop moving to Docker is control over the build environment rather than host utilization. Being able to set up what tools are available (findbugs ,shellcheck, etc) and what libraries are ready (e.g. for native builds) is the big win.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14554902" author="apurtell" created="Thu, 21 May 2015 19:19:27 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Being able to set up what tools are available (findbugs ,shellcheck, etc) and what libraries are ready (e.g. for native builds) is the big win.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think we should explore this because of the potential to improve test repeatability.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
